Package com.teksystems.salestaxexercise.tax

Class SalesTax

java.lang.Object
com.teksystems.salestaxexercise.tax.SalesTax
All Implemented Interfaces:
Tax
Direct Known Subclasses:
ImportSalesTax
public class SalesTax
extends java.lang.Object
implements Tax
Generic implementation of a simple sales tax. Should be able to be used for most simple sales taxes in most jurisdictions. TODO: the most basic sales tax would have no exempted categories. Remove the exemptions from this class, and make a separate abstract class (and separate interface) that adds exemptions to it.
Author:
Andrew

  • Constructor Details

    • SalesTax

      public SalesTax​(TaxJurisdiction taxJurisdiction, java.lang.String name, java.math.BigDecimal percentage, java.util.Set<TaxableCategory> exemptedCategories, java.math.RoundingMode roundingMode, MoneyRoundingRule customRoundingRule)
      Constructor for a generic sales tax TODO: should implement the Builder design pattern on this class to simplify construction The percentage parameter should represent the actual percent number for this tax, NOT the multiplier corresponding to that percentage. e.g. for a 10.5% sales tax, percentage should be 10.5, NOT the equivalent multiplier 0.105
      Parameters:
      taxJurisdiction - the tax jurisdiction in which this tax applies, required
      name - the name of of this tax, required and must be non-empty
      percentage - the percentage for this sales tax (not divided by 100), required and must be non-zero
      exemptedCategories - the set of taxable categories that are exempt from this tax, optional
      roundingMode - the rounding mode for this tax, optional, defaults to RoundingMode.HALF_UP
      customRoundingRule - any custom rounding rule that should be applied to this tax, optional

    • getTaxAmountFor

      public org.joda.money.Money getTaxAmountFor​(SellableItem sellableItem)
      Description copied from interface: Tax
      Get the amount of this tax for the specified sellable item. TODO: does this method really need to take a sellable item as its parameter, could possibly take the more generic Sellable interface instead? Some taxes might exist which apply to a collection of goods (or services) rather than to each specific item in that collection separately? The only reason I really need a SellableItem here, for the limited purposes of this specific exercise, is because I need the SellableItem.getRegionOfOrigin() function for the import duty... and I'm not even sure that method belongs in that interface anyway.
      Specified by:
      getTaxAmountFor in interface Tax
      Parameters:
      sellableItem - the item to which this tax will be applied
      Returns:
